        <div class="seo-content">
            <h2>How This Credit Card Payoff Calculator Works</h2>
            <p>Enter your current credit card balance, APR, and monthly payment to see exactly how long it will take to become debt-free. The calculator uses standard monthly compounding — your APR is divided by 12 to determine monthly interest, which is applied to your outstanding balance each month. Your payment is first applied to interest, with the remainder reducing your principal.</p>
            <p>If you select "Minimum Payment Only," the calculator simulates the declining minimum payment that most credit card companies use (typically 1-3% of the balance, with a floor of $25). This reveals the minimum payment trap — how paying only the minimum stretches your payoff over decades and costs a fortune in interest.</p>

            <h2>Understanding Credit Card Interest</h2>
            <p>Credit card interest is one of the most expensive forms of consumer debt. The average credit card APR in the US is over 20%, meaning a $5,000 balance accrues roughly $83 in interest in the first month alone. Because minimum payments are calculated as a small percentage of the balance, most of your minimum payment goes toward interest rather than reducing what you owe.</p>
            <p>This creates a compounding problem: high interest charges mean slow principal reduction, which means the balance stays high, which means interest charges stay high. Breaking this cycle requires paying significantly more than the minimum.</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>$5,000 at 22% APR, $200/month:</strong> Paid off in about 31 months, ~$1,100 total interest</li>
                <li><strong>$5,000 at 22% APR, $100/month:</strong> Paid off in about 93 months (7.75 years), ~$4,300 total interest</li>
                <li><strong>$5,000 at 22% APR, minimum only:</strong> Could take 20+ years and cost more than the original balance in interest</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Balance Transfer: When Does It Make Sense?</h2>
            <p>A balance transfer to a 0% intro APR card can be a powerful tool, but it's not always the right move. It makes sense when: your current APR is high (15%+), you can pay off all or most of the balance during the intro period, and the transfer fee (typically 3-5%) is less than the interest you'd save. The calculator's balance transfer section does this math for you automatically.</p>
            <p>Be cautious of the post-intro APR. If you can't pay off the balance during the promotional period, you'll be right back where you started — possibly at an even higher rate. Always have a plan to eliminate the balance before the intro period expires.</p>
